Here's the complete migration with key pitfalls explained:

## ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Migration

```csharp
// ReportController.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // PITFALL 1: No more WebForms event handlers (btnExport_Click).
    // ASP.NET Core uses action methods routed via HTTP verbs.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        // PITFALL 2: Response.Clear(), Response.Write(), Response.End()
        // don't exist. Return an IActionResult instead — the framework
        // handles headers and streaming.
        var data = GenerateReport();
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
    {
        // PITFALL 3: Response.Redirect("/login", true) used to call
        // Thread.Abort() to stop execution. ASP.NET Core never aborts
        // threads — RedirectResult just sets a 302 and returns normally.
        // No ThreadAbortException exists. Guard with early returns.
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // PITFALL 4: Remove the ThreadAbortException catch entirely.
        // It was only needed because Response.Redirect(url, true) threw
        // it. In ASP.NET Core, redirects are just return values — no
        // exception is ever thrown.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() => /* ... */ "";
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls Summary

| .NET Framework Pattern | Problem in .NET 8 | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Doesn't exist; relied on `Thread.Abort` | Return `IActionResult` instead |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | No `endResponse` param; no thread abort | Return `Redirect()` + early `return` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Type doesn't exist in .NET 8 | Delete the catch block entirely |
| `Response.Write(data)` | No synchronous write to response body | Use `File()`, `Content()`, or write to `Response.Body` |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | Method removed | Use `Response.Headers.Append(...)` if manual headers are needed |
| `btnExport_Click` event handlers | WebForms lifecycle doesn't exist | Use `[HttpPost]` / `[HttpGet]` action methods |

## Control Flow Change (the big gotcha)

In Framework, `Response.Redirect(url, true)` and `Response.End()` **stopped execution mid-method** via `Thread.Abort`. Code after them never ran. In .NET 8, redirects are just return values — **code after a `Redirect()` call keeps executing** unless you explicitly `return`. Every redirect must be a `return Redirect(...)`.

```csharp
// WRONG — code after Redirect() still executes in .NET 8!
Redirect("/login");
DoSensitiveWork(); // THIS STILL RUNS

// CORRECT
return Redirect("/login");
```

## Registration (Program.cs)

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
builder.Services.AddControllersWithViews();

var app = builder.Build();
app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();
app.MapControllerRoute("default", "{controller=Home}/{action=Index}/{id?}");
app.Run();
```

The core mental model shift: **ASP.NET Core never aborts threads**. All response writing is done via return values (`IActionResult`), not imperative calls to `Response`. Every place the old code relied on execution stopping mid-method needs an explicit `return`.
